did.abstract: This collection documents the work and performances of the American Wind Symphony Orchestra, founded in 1957 by conductor Robert Boudreau. The records in the collection include fundraising documents, personnel records, programs, publicity, financial records, project files, and photos, along with substantial documentation of the AWSO's tours and performances between 1960 and the late 1980s. There is also some audio and video documentation of performances by the AWSO.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: Access to the following records is restricted until 75 years after the date of creation: Personnel records and applications in Series III, Subseries 2 and employee tax documents in Series IV. Until then researchers can access the records by signing a confidentiality agreement. Please contact Archives & Special Collections for more information.

bioghist.head: History
bioghist.p: The American Wind Symphony Orchestra (AWSO) was founded by Robert Boudreau in 1957, after he moved to Pittsburgh to teach at Duquesne University. He envisioned a "floating orchestra," which would perform from a barge at docks and ports, taking high-level instrumental music outside of the concert hall to communities across the country. The AWSO was initially funded by the H.J. Heinz company and Duquesne University and performed their first season's shows from a converted coal barge named Point Counterpoint. The original barge was replaced by Point Counterpoint II in 1976 during the United States Bicentennial. Still an active performing organization in 2017, the American Wind Symphony has performed throughout America, Canada, Europe, and the Caribbean for over 50 years, commissioning over 400 new compositions and arrangements. The AWSO remains a committed proponent of the wind symphony repertoire through its active program of commissions and performances, as well as American Wind Symphony Editions, which sells musical scores, many arranged or composed for the AWSO.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: The records of the American Wind Symphony Orchestra (AWSO) document the organization's creative work, programming, and public stature from its founding in 1957 through 2012, with particular focus on the group's administration, personnel, performances, and special projects. Taken together, the records document the popularity and growth of the organization through personnel records and biographies of performers, commissioned works, concert programs and advertising, as well as administrative records such as correspondence and financial records. Of particular note is the large volume of correspondence to and from the AWSO regarding sponsorship and funding, compositions and commissions, advertisements, performances, and other administrative issues. Additionally, the personnel records, project files, and concert programs document the group's artistic work through biographies and applications of AWSO members and guest artists, an extensive run of concert programs and program notes, information about particular concert venues at which the AWSO performed, and records about educational programs, festivals, and other special events planned and carried out by AWSO. Finally, the photographs and audiovisual media, including headshots and professional photos, candid photographs, and audio and film recordings of AWSO performances, lend visual and auditory context to the other record series in the collection.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This series contains incoming and outgoing correspondence from the American Wind Symphony Orchestra. While the subjects of correspondence are varied, common topics are logistics and advertisement for upcoming performances, letters between the AWSO and composers or guest artists, correspondence and memos about the work of the AWSO board and committees, and fundraising requests and acknowledgements. The records in this series are arranged in chronological order.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This series contains information about the finances of the American Wind Symphony Orchestra, including budgets, tax information, financial statements, and insurance information. Of particular note are the folders relating to the construction, financing, and insurance for Point Counterpont II, the barge/performance space that was created for AWSO in 1976. The series is arranged chronologically.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This series documents the American Wind Symphony Orchestra's fundraising efforts, including correspondence with donors and potential donors, budget and tax records, and checks. Some folders also contain annual reports and other documentation from organizations that funded the AWSO. This series is arranged in chronological order.

did.unittitle: Executive Committee and Board of Directors

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: Series contains minutes, correspondence, member lists and notes from the AWSO Board of Directors and Executive Committee. It also contains a copy of the By-Laws of the AWSO.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This series contains information largely about the performing personnel of the American Wind Symphony Orchestra, including brief biographies for musicians selected for AWSO concerts and tours, personnel files, and applications from instrumentalists, many of which contain handwritten notes about their auditions. This series has been arranged into two subseries. The first contains correspondence with, biographical sketches of, and contracts with guest artists, commissioned composers, and other AWSO collaborators. The second contains applications, contracts, correspondence, and biographical information from musicians hired by AWSO.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This sub series contains correspondence, biographical sketches, and other information on guest artists who performed with the AWSO, composers commissioned by AWSO, and other special guests involved in AWSO tours or performances. This subseries is organized alphabetically.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This sub series contains general information on instrumental performers of the American Wind Symphony, who were generally hired for a particular season or festival. It contains applications, along with notes on auditions, signed contracts, correspondence, and brief biographies of performers. This sub series is arranged chronologically by year.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This series contains programs from the American Wind Symphony Orchestra's performances, some for individual concerts and some for tours comprising many individual concerts. Also included in this series are drafts and early versions of program notes, as well as correspondence with companies discussing advertising placement in AWSO's programs. The series is arranged chronologically.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This series contains information on the Women's Association of the American Wind Symphony Orchestra, an organization dedicated to supporting and promoting the Orchestra. Series contains correspondence, tax records, bylaws, member lists, and pamphlets.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This series contains publicity about the American Wind Symphony Orchestra, including news clippings, from the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette, New York Times, and local and regional papers that covered AWSO's performances. There are also magazines featuring articles on the AWSO, pamphlets and flyers advertising concerts and other events, and AWSO press releases.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains original newspaper clippings and photocopies of newspaper clippings about the American Wind Symphony Orchestra from local, national, and regional publications. This subseries has been arranged chronologically by year.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains articles about the American Wind Symphony Orchestra from various national and local magazines. The records in this subseries are kept in chronological order by decade.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: The subseries contains flyers and booklets created for patrons of American Wind Symphony Orchestra concerts. This sub series has been arranged into four folders by year.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains American Wind Symphony Orchestra press releases and other advertising material from 1959-1985, including announcements of upcoming concerts, tours, and some texts for radio advertisements. This subseries has been arranged chronologically by year.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains scrapbooks made in the 1960s for the American Wind Symphony Orchestra for the years 1960-1961. The scrapbooks contain mostly copies of newspaper, and magazine clippings about the orchestra or the orchestra's concerts.

did.unittitle: Educational Programs, Festivals, and Other Projects

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This series contains information about special events, educational programs, and festivals organized by the American Wind Symphony Orchestra. Most notably, this series has documentation on the Floating Center of the Arts barge project, Pennsylvania Artist Exhibition, and the AWSO's Caribbean Scholar Program. The content of folders is varied, but folders generally contain correspondence, invitations, photographs, flyers, pamphlets, press releases, and handwritten notes. This series is arranged chronologically by year.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This series contains records about American Wind Symphony Orchestra's performances and tours from the 1960s until the 1980s, as well as correspondence discussing the possibility of concerts with local governments, businesses, and civic groups. There are folders that pertain to entire tours, and other folders that contain information, correspondence, publicity, and other records from locations at which the AWSO played, including locations in the United States, Canada, Central America, and the Caribbean. Folders contain correspondence, budget documents, handwritten notes, AWSO member lists, lists of performing locations, maps, schedules, newspaper clippings, pamphlets and programs. Folders pertaining to tours have been arranged chronologically, while folders about individual cities are arranged alphabetically.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This series contains photographs, slides, contact sheets, and negatives that depict AWSO's performances, guest artists, tours, and performance venues. Many photos are promotional shots from professional photographers, though there are some amateur photographs included, as well. There are many photographs of Robert Boudreau, AWSO's conductor, as well as shots of the ensemble performing, the Point Counterpoint and Point Counterpoint II barges, guest artists, and performance venues. The series has been divided into three subseries. The first contains print photographs of AWSO performers, guest artists, and other people associated with the ensemble; the second contains photogrpahic prints of performances, tours, and of Point Counterpoint I and II; the third contains other photographic formats such as negatives, contact prints, and printing plates.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains images of instrumentalists who played with the AWSO as well as guest artists, performers, and conductors.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains topical photographs of individual concerts, performances, or tours as well as several images of Point Counterpoint I and Point Counterpoint II.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Notes
scopecontent.p: This series contains moving image material from the American Wind Symphony Orchestra. Some of the film contains footage of the Floating Center for the Arts, the launch of Counterpoint II, and performances of the AWSO. While other film is unlabeled and the contents are unknown, it is likely that the rest of the film contains footage from AWSO tours and performances, or of AWSO special events.
